Circular Queue Implementation in C++
=====================================

A circular queue is a type of queue data structure where the last element is connected to the first element, forming a circle. Here is a C++ implementation of a circular queue using a fixed-size array.

### Circular Queue Class

```cpp
#include <iostream>

template <typename T>
class CircularQueue {
private:
    int front, rear, size, capacity;
    T* queue;

public:
    // Constructor
    CircularQueue(int capacity) : capacity(capacity), front(0), rear(0), size(0) {
        queue = new T[capacity];
    }

    // Destructor
    ~CircularQueue() {
        delete[] queue;
    }

    // Enqueue an element
    void enqueue(T data) {
        if (isFull()) {
            std::cerr << "Queue is full. Cannot enqueue." << std::endl;
            return;
        }

        queue[rear] = data;
        rear = (rear + 1) % capacity;
        size++;
    }

    // Dequeue an element
    T dequeue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            std::cerr << "Queue is empty. Cannot dequeue." << std::endl;
            exit(1); // or throw an exception
        }

        T data = queue[front];
        front = (front + 1) % capacity;
        size--;
        return data;
    }

    // Check if the queue is empty
    bool isEmpty() const {
        return size == 0;
    }

    // Check if the queue is full
    bool isFull() const {
        return size == capacity;
    }

    // Get the front element
    T getFront() const {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            std::cerr << "Queue is empty." << std::endl;
            exit(1); // or throw an exception
        }

        return queue[front];
    }

    // Get the rear element
    T getRear() const {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            std::cerr << "Queue is empty." << std::endl;
            exit(1); // or throw an exception
        }

        return queue[(rear - 1 + capacity) % capacity];
    }

    // Get the size of the queue
    int getSize() const {
        return size;
    }
};
```

### Example Use Cases

```cpp
int main() {
    // Create a circular queue with a capacity of 5
    CircularQueue<int> queue(5);

    // Enqueue elements
    queue.enqueue(1);
    queue.enqueue(2);
    queue.enqueue(3);
    queue.enqueue(4);
    queue.enqueue(5);

    // Dequeue elements
    std::cout << "Dequeued: " << queue.dequeue() << std::endl; // prints 1
    std::cout << "Dequeued: " << queue.dequeue() << std::endl; // prints 2

    // Enqueue more elements
    queue.enqueue(6);
    queue.enqueue(7);

    // Get the front and rear elements
    std::cout << "Front: " << queue.getFront() << std::endl; // prints 3
    std::cout << "Rear: " << queue.getRear() << std::endl; // prints 7

    // Get the size of the queue
    std::cout << "Size: " << queue.getSize() << std::endl; // prints 5

    return 0;
}
```

This implementation provides basic operations for a circular queue, including `enqueue`, `dequeue`, `isEmpty`, `isFull`, `getFront`, `getRear`, and `getSize`. The example use cases demonstrate how to create a circular queue, enqueue and dequeue elements, and retrieve the front and rear elements.

Here is a simple implementation of a dynamic array in Rust that supports the `collect()` method.

```rust
// Define a simple dynamic array struct
struct DynamicArray<T> {
    data: Vec<T>,
}

impl<T> DynamicArray<T> {
    // Create a new dynamic array
    fn new() -> Self {
        DynamicArray { data: Vec::new() }
    }

    // Push an element onto the array
    fn push(&mut self, element: T) {
        self.data.push(element);
    }

    // Get a reference to the internal vector
    fn as_vec(&self) -> &Vec<T> {
        &self.data
    }
}

// Implement the FromIterator trait to support collect()
impl<T> FromIterator<T> for DynamicArray<T> {
    fn from_iter<I: IntoIterator<Item = T>>(iter: I) -> Self {
        let mut array = DynamicArray::new();
        for element in iter {
            array.push(element);
        }
        array
    }
}

fn main() {
    // Create a dynamic array from an iterator
    let array: DynamicArray<i32> = (1..10).collect();
    println!("{:?}", array.as_vec()); // prints: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9]
}
```

This implementation defines a `DynamicArray` struct that wraps a `Vec` and provides methods for pushing elements onto the array and getting a reference to the internal vector. The `FromIterator` trait is implemented to support the `collect()` method.

The `main()` function demonstrates how to create a `DynamicArray` from an iterator using the `collect()` method.

